			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Well, I have yet to try hill or sand giants, but I've tried soloing frost giant scouts in GD (bad idea, because its waaaay too easy to get a wolf or another giant as an add), and based on that, I'd like to make the following comments:
<br />

<br />
Fire pet is a bad choice to use if you're soloing giants unless you're sure you won't get adds. Since it has the least hit points of the 4 pets, you're not going to have time to gate while it holds off the mobs, even if its focused and you've put Phantom Plate on it and cast Burnout II.
<br />

<br />
I have to agree focused Air is the way to go due to its agility, and equipping it with Phantom Plate is a must. The Water pet is an okay choice if you don't have the Air pet, but Air is MUCH better. 
<br />
Earth should NEVER be used unless you're in a decent group that has at least one meleeing PC who can taunt. (And even then, I wouldn't recommend it - I use Air or Fire when hunting giants in a group) Fire's a good choice if there's another pet class in the group. Their pet taunts while yours doesn't, and you let your pet's DS chew through the mob's health by telling it to taunt while they pull back their pet to heal it if necessary.
<br />

<br />
Earth may be able to root and have more hit points, but its going to get hit by every one of the giant's attacks. If you have KEI and would like to spend most of the fight healing your pet rather than nuking, go for it, but your pet will still probably die.
<br />

<br />
And no matter what pet you use, make sure you keep yourself damage shielded if you don't have SoW or Jboots. I've yet to fight giants, solo or in a group, without getting hit at least once during a session if I didn't have a speed buff.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
